e book’s key aims is to show how the colonial Church should be of interest to more than just scholars and students of religious and Church history. The colonial Church was an institution that played a vital role in the formation of political publics and ethnic communities in a settler empire that was being remoulded by the advent of mass migration, democracy and the separation of Church and State.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAnglican CommunionxColonieszGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 0aAnglican CommunionxColonieszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aAnglican Church.  aBishops.  aBritish world.  aChurch reform.  aClergy.  aColonial settler society.  aEmpire.  aInstitutional Church.  aPolitical reform.  aSettlers.1 aHardwick, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packagez978311128357940uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978071909712640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780719097126423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780719097126/original  a978-3-11-128357-9  Manchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packageb2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles